<section class="card">
  <h2>Colorado Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Colorado gardening is strongly influenced by elevation and local terrain. Many parts of the state
    sit well above 5,000 feet, which reduces heat accumulation and increases the chance of late spring
    and early fall frost. Even when daytime temperatures feel warm, cool nights can slow crop
    development and shorten the effective growing season.
  </p>

  <p>
    Because of this, successful planting decisions in Colorado usually depend on how well crop maturity
    fits the remaining seasonal heat rather than simply counting frost-free days.
  </p>

  <h3>1) Elevation shortens the effective growing season</h3>

  <p>
    Higher elevations experience cooler average temperatures and slower heat accumulation.
    Gardens at 6,000–7,000 feet may accumulate far fewer growing degree days than nearby
    lower valleys, even when they share similar frost dates.
  </p>

  <p>
    This difference explains why the same crop variety can mature easily in one part of the state
    but struggle in another. If you're gardening at elevation, it helps to understand
    <a href="/guides/how-elevation-affects-growing-degree-days/">
      how elevation changes growing degree day accumulation
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Frost pockets are common along the Front Range</h3>

  <p>
    Cold air drains downhill during clear nights and collects in low areas. As a result,
    valley bottoms and low neighborhoods often experience earlier frost than nearby slopes
    or slightly elevated sites.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two gardens only a few blocks apart can have noticeably different frost timing,
    especially in foothill communities. These local variations are a classic example of
    <a href="/guides/how-microclimates-change-frost-dates/">
      how microclimates can shift frost dates
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>3) Summer heat builds quickly but nights stay cool</h3>

  <p>
    Colorado summers can accumulate growing degree days rapidly during sunny stretches.
    However, nighttime temperatures frequently drop into the 50s or even 40s, especially
    at elevation. These cool nights slow heat accumulation compared to warmer low-elevation
    climates.
  </p>

  <p>
    Crops planted early enough to take advantage of June and July heat typically perform well,
    but late plantings may struggle to ripen before fall frost.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Variety choice matters more than planting date</h3>

  <p>
    In many Colorado gardens, choosing shorter-season crop varieties makes a bigger difference
    than planting a few days earlier or later. A tomato that matures in 60–70 days may ripen
    consistently where an 85-day variety struggles.
  </p>

  <p>
    That’s because days-to-maturity labels assume steady warmth. In cooler climates,
    development slows when overnight temperatures drop, which is one reason
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">
      maturity days alone can be misleading
    </a>.
  </p>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    Use the frost timing and remaining heat data above as a baseline,
    then compare crop maturity requirements against the remaining growing degree days
    available for your location.
  </p>
</section>